text: I was concerned after reading the two other 1-star reviews about the taste and quality.  I had purchased a two pound bag of  shrimp from Whole Foods.  However, I think that Dominick's Seafood Inc is only the packaging plant.  I have been purchasing wild shrimp for over 20 years from various high quality supermarkets.  These were succulent and large with lots of flavor.  The value was excellent at $11.00 pound for 16-20 count.  HEB in comparison sells 30-40 count for the around the same price.    These 16-20 variety has lots more flavor than smaller varieties.

text: Hands down Dominick's is the best frozen shrimp I've ever bought. The other brands like Cape Gourmet, taste like garbage. When you boil Dominick's you get firm, fresh tasting shrimp. The other brands that come from shrimp farms in Asia seem to be mushy and just don't taste right.

name: Veronica Rabideau- Standeven
text: The Best Frozen Shrimp!!! I had fresh caught shrimp down in Virginia & loved the taste & texture! The difference (other than being fresh)??? The is NO Trisodium Phosphate used as a 'preservative'. TSP makes shrimp less firm, kind of watery & less flavorful. If you are looking for shrimp that taste as close to fresh as you can get (especially us Mid-Westerners!!!), this will not disappoint! If you have ONLY experienced frozen shrimp with TSP added as a preservative, these will taste different to you. I think that may be why others reviewers had a low rating....

name: Pamela Denise Brown - Pamela In The Light

I Bought Them,  Because They Were Deveined,  But I Will NEVER By Them Again...
I'll Peel And Devein My Own Shrimp,  As Long As They're From Dominicks Seafood...

text: This is the only place I buy seafood now, if you haven’t been, you definitely need to. For quality of product, it literally can’t be beat!  They get everything in fresh, they steam it for you if you want, and their crawfish brine is TO DIE FOR!  They also sell the brine for you to cook on your own at home if you’d rather. They have all the spices to do Cajun right, and the staff couldn’t be more helpful or knowledgeable. Joe is always at the counter and you’ll never meet anyone who knows more about seafood. I can’t rave about this place enough, it’s clean, convenient, and better freshness and quality of seafood in Birmingham, you’ll never find!

Fresh Gulf seafood!

name: Stacey Brown
text:
I decided to shop local instead of Whole Foods on hwy 280 in search for whole red snapper. They did have red snapper and was able to prepare it for cooking just as Whole Foods does. Their prices are higher than Whole Foods which wasn't a deal breaker. We purchased 2 whole red snapper at $52.61 and a half of filet of Salmon at $27.13. They politely provided ice for the ride as requested. Before we could get home we started smelling a foul smell from the fish. This has never happened on our ride from Whole Foods which is a farther distance. We are not fish experts by any means- just seafood lovers. Anyone who does fish would know that one of the fish that we were sold was spoiled and should not be eaten. Definitely an owner or employee of a seafood market would know this. I did some research to determine the signs of bad fish (Spoiled fish has an unpleasant, sharp smell of trimethylamine (bad fish) and rot. Eyes of fresh fish are bulging and shiny. Eyes of old fish are cloudy and sunken into the head. Gills and fins of fresh fish are moist).
One of our fish had all of the signs listed (I posted pictures of the two snappers we were sold).
So what was meant for dinner for two is now dinner for one for @ $52.61.
This was my first and last experience at the Hoover Seafood Market.

name: Gina Lymburner
text:
I tried the Cornbread Stuffing and was really pleased to taste quality ingredients right off the bat.  I am a long line of Tennessee women that take great pride in their cooking abilities.  I believe if I served this cornbread from Carrington Foods that everyone would think I made it from scratch.

Serve with pot roast, smoked pork chops, smoked turkey, steak and with just about any kind of chicken.  I serve it with many different kinds of greens such as mustard greens, kale, turnip greens and callaloo all cooked with loads of caramelized onions and roasted garlic.  I try to go meatless 3 days out of the week and have found the wonderful home cooked taste and texture of the cornbread stuffing makes me not even miss the meat.

Seriously do yourself a favor and give it a try, you will be glad you did.
